Pantur Silaban is one of the foremost physicists in Indonesia , especially in the field of theoretical physics .

Modesta Lavana Pérez ( February 24 , 1929 - December 13 , 2010 ) was an indigenous Nahua healer and activist from the town of Hueyapan , Morelos , Mexico .
Hilarios Karl - Heinz Ungerer ( born 1941 in Nuremberg ) is a Free Catholic Church in Germany bishop in Munich , though he ministered through other independent European churches .
Born in Bordeaux , Aquitaine , France , Pierre Rode traveled to Paris at the age of 13 and soon became a favourite pupil of the great Giovanni Battista Viotti , who found the boy so talented that he charged him no fee for the lessons .
Ľudovít Lancz ( 2 June 1964 -- 20 July 2004 ) was a football player who played for the Czechoslovakia national football team .
Franco Forini ( born 22 September 1958 in Muralto ) is a former racing driver from Switzerland .
William Henry Jackson ( May 3 , 1861 -- January 10 , 1952 ) , also known as Honoré Jackson or Jaxon , was secretary to Louis Riel during the North - West Rebellion in Canada in 1885 .
Jörg Siebert ( born on April 2 , 1944 ) is a competition rower and Olympic champion for West Germany .
Paulo Avelino was born on May 13 , 1988 as Michael Paulo Lingbanan Avelino in Baguio City , Philippines .
Tomasz Mędrzak ( born December 18 , 1954 in Łódź , Poland ) , was a teenage star of the 1973 In Desert and Wilderness movie and miniseries ( 1973 ) , where he played Staś Tarkowski , having Monika Rosca as young partner .
The Virgin of the Navigators ( Spanish : La Virgen de los Navegantes ) is a painting by Spanish artist Alejo Fernández , created as the central panel of an altarpiece for the chapel of the Casa de Contratación building in Seville , southern Spain .
In 2009 , Mill Creek Entertainment acquired the rights to several Stephen J. Cannell series , including The Commish .
Imbestigador ( English : Investigator ) is an investigative show broadcast by GMA Network .
Inspector Salvo Montalbano ( Italian : commissario Salvo Montalbano ) is a fictional character created by Italian writer Andrea Camilleri in a series of novels and short stories .
Le Service après - vente des émissions or SAV des émissions is a French short comedy television series hosted by the comic duo Omar and Fred ( Omar Sy and Fred Testot ) since 2005 on Canal+ .
Test Site was designed like Carsten Höller , and was the seventh commission of the series of works in the turbine hall sponsored by Unilever known as `` The Unilever Series '' .
Cairn in Snow ( German : Hünengrab i m Schnee ) is a landscape painting by Caspar David Friedrich .
The Jim Morrison Triptych is an oil painting by American artist T. E. Breitenbach ( best known for his painting Proverbidioms ) .
Cold Lazarus is a four - part British television drama written by Dennis Potter with the knowledge that he was dying of cancer of the pancreas .
Man and Woman in Front of a Pile of Excrement ( Homme et femme devant un tas d'excréments ) is a 1935 oil painting on copper by Joan Miró .
Vorhor , the Green Wave is one of the most famous paintings by French artist Georges Lacombe .
Elric of Melniboné is a fictional character created by Michael Moorcock and the protagonist of a series of sword and sorcery stories taking place on an alternate Earth .
Campbell 's Soup Cans , which is sometimes referred to as 32 Campbell 's Soup Cans , is a work of art produced in 1962 by Andy Warhol .
The Child 's Bath ( or The Bath ) is an 1893 oil painting by American artist Mary Cassatt .
The Alba Madonna is a painting by the Italian High Renaissance artist Raphael , depicting Mary , Jesus and John the Baptist , in a typical Italian countryside .
Meg Giry is one of the fictional characters from Gaston Leroux 's novel The Phantom of the Opera .
Still Life with Head - Shaped Vase and Japanese Woodcut is an 1889 still life painting by French artist , Paul Gauguin .
The West Wing is an American serial political drama television series created by Aaron Sorkin that was originally broadcast on NBC from September 22 , 1999 , to May 14 , 2006 .
Keeping Up Appearances is a British sitcom created and written by Roy Clarke for the BBC , centred on the life of eccentric and snobbish middle class social climber Hyacinth Bucket , who insists that her surname is pronounced `` Bouquet '' .
The Ren & Stimpy Show , often simply referred to as Ren & Stimpy , is an American animated television series created by John Kricfalusi for Nickelodeon .
Game of Thrones is an American fantasy drama television series created by showrunners David Benioff and D. B. Weiss .
The Portrait of Maria Anna is a 1630 portrait of Maria Anna of Spain by Diego Velázquez .
The Miracle of the Cross at the Bridge of S. Lorenzo ( Italian : Miracolo della Croce caduta nel canale di San Lorenzo ) is a painting by Italian Renaissance artist Gentile Bellini , dating from 1500 .

Two of the Natives of New Holland , Advancing to Combat is a drawing by Sydney Parkinson , drawn in 1770 and published posthumously in 1773 .
Saint Teresa of Ávila 's Vision of the Holy Spirit is a 1612 - 1614 painting by Peter Paul Rubens .
The Madonna of the Animals is a c.1503 drawing on card by the artist Albrecht Dürer , measuring 32 by 24 cm . Some areas of the drawing also feature watercolour .
Girl in Mirror ( sometimes Girl in the Mirror ) is a 1964 porcelain - enamel - on - steel pop art painting by Roy Lichtenstein that is considered to exist in between eight and ten editions .
Lincoln in Dalivision is an original limited edition lithograph created by Salvador Dalí .
The Mature Age , also named The Destiny , The Way of Life or The Fate ( 1894 - 1900 ) is one of major sculptures by Camille Claudel .

Madonna of the Rose Bower ( or Virgin in the Rose Bower ) is a panel painting by the German artits Stefan Lochner , usually dated c 1440 - 42 , although some art historians believe it contemporaneous with his later Dombild Altarpiece .
Inside No . 9 is a British dark comedy anthology television programme written by Reece Shearsmith and Steve Pemberton and produced by the BBC .
The Portrait of Olivia Boteler Porter is an oil painting on canvas by Anthony van Dyck , showing Olivia Boteler Porter .
The remnants of an army , Jellalabad , January 13 , 1842 , better known as Remnants of an Army , is an 1879 oil - on - canvas painting by Elizabeth Thompson , Lady Butler .

The Bold and the Beautiful ( often referred to as B&B ) is an American television soap opera created by William J. Bell and Lee Phillip Bell for CBS .
Le Dépiquage des Moissons , also known as Harvest Threshing , and The Harvesters , is an immense oil painting created in 1912 by the French artist , theorist and writer Albert Gleizes ( 1881 - -1953 ) .
The Sphere is a large metallic sculpture by German sculptor Fritz Koenig , displayed in Battery Park , New York City , that once stood in the middle of Austin J. Tobin Plaza , the area between the World Trade Center towers in Manhattan .
The Blacksmith 's Shop is a recurring theme of five paintings by Joseph Wright of Derby .
The Separation of Light from Darkness is , from the perspective of the Genesis chronology , the first of nine central panels that run along the center of Michelangelo 's Sistine Chapel ceiling and which depict scenes from the Book of Genesis .

George Washington on Horseback is an equestrian statue by sculptor Herbert Haseltine .
Great Old Amusement Parks is a 1999 PBS television documentary VHS by Rick Sebak of WQED Pittsburgh .
Portrait of Yevgeny Mravinsky is a painting by Russian portrait artist Lev Russov ( 1926 - -1987 ) , whose work depicts the famous Russian and Soviet musician Yevgeny Aleksandrovich Mravinsky ( 1903 - -1988 ) , principal conductor of the Leningrad Philharmonic Orchestra in 1938 - -1988 years .
Wild Instinct ( Les Zooriginaux in French ) is a children 's television series produced by Procidis about a group of animals living in a zoo .
The Bust of Alessandro Peretti di Montalto is a portrait sculpture by the Italian artist Gian Lorenzo Bernini .
The Insensitive Princess ( French : La Princesse insensible ) is a 1983 French animated television series written and directed by Michel Ocelot .
Nighthawks is a 1942 oil on canvas painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people in a downtown diner late at night .
The Three Philosophers is an oil painting on canvas attributed to the Italian High Renaissance artist Giorgione .
The Yellow House ( Dutch : Het gele huis ) , alternatively named The Street ( Dutch : De straat ) , is an 1888 oil painting by the 19th - century Dutch Post - Impressionist painter Vincent van Gogh .

Portrait of Dr. Gachet is one of the most revered paintings by the Dutch artist Vincent van Gogh .
The Baron is a British television series , made in 1965/66 based on the book series by John Creasey , written under the pseudonym Anthony Morton , and produced by ITC Entertainment .
`` Hold On ( To My Love ) '' is a song written by Robin Gibb and Blue Weaver and performed by American soul singer Jimmy Ruffin , released in 1980 on his album Sunrise .
Sunlight in the Blue Room ( Danish : Solskin i den blå stue ) is an 1891 painting by Anna Ancher , an innovative Danish painter who was a central figure with the Skagen Painters .
The Solly Madonna by the Italian renaissance artist Raphael was painted somewhere between 1500 and 1504 .

Margalit Fox ( born 1961 ) is an American writer for The New York Times , and other publications , and is a book author .
Vincent Broderick ( 17 August 1920 -- 14 November 2010 ) , known as Vince Broderick , was an English cricketer who played for Northamptonshire and briefly for the MCC .
Samuel Hardy ( 1758 -- October 17 , 1785 ) was an American lawyer and statesman from Virginia , who served as a delegate to the Continental Congress .

Clement Melville Keys ( 1876 - -1952 ) who as a financier was involved with founding of aviation companies Curtiss - Wright , China National Aviation Corporation , North American Aviation and TWA .

Thomas Walkley ( fl . 1618 -- 1658 ) was a London publisher and bookseller in the early and middle seventeenth century .

Maurine Whipple ( 20 January 1903 -- 12 April 1992 ) was a twentieth - century American novelist and short story writer best known for her novel The Giant Joshua ( 1941 ) about southern Utah and polygamy .
Fotis Polymeris ( Patras , 20 February 1920 - Athens , 28 May 2013 ) , born as Fotis Palymeris , was a Greek guitarist , singer and composer .

Rabbi Sidney Brichto ( 21 July 1936 -- 16 January 2009 ) was a British Liberal rabbi .
Charles Dieupart ( after 1667 -- 1740 ) was a French harpsichordist , violinist , and composer .
Dorothy Hammerstein ( 7 June 1899 -- 3 August 1987 ) was an Australian - born American interior designer and decorator .
Group Captain Colin Falkland Gray DSO , DFC & Two Bars ( 9 November 1914 -- 1 August 1995 ) was the top New Zealand fighter ace of the Second World War .
Henry de Beltgens Gibbins ( 1865 - -1907 ) was a popular historian of 19th century England whose books were bestsellers in the late Victorian period ; his Industry in England went to ten editions over fifteen years , and was published internationally .
Francis Mundy ( 29 August 1771 -- 6 May 1837 ) was a landowner , member of parliament for Derbyshire and a High Sheriff of Derbyshire .
Richard Barry , 2nd Earl of Barrymore , 7th Viscount Buttevant , 20th Baron Barry ( 4 November 1630 -- 1694 ) was the son of David Barry , 1st Earl of Barrymore and Lady Alice Boyle .

John Hope , 2nd Earl of Hopetoun ( 7 September 1704 -- 12 February 1781 ) was the son of Charles Hope , 1st Earl of Hopetoun and Lady Henrietta Johnstone .
Mercedes Sola ( 1879 - -1923 ) was a Puerto Rican writer , educator , and activist for the rights of women .
Onslow Burrish ( died 1758 ) was a British envoy in the Low Countries and Germany .
Meyer Schleifer ( 1908 - -1994 ) was an American bridge player from Los Angeles , California .
Lilian Bader ( 18 February 1918 -- 13 March 2015 ) was one of the first black women to join the British armed forces .
Nilu Phule ( died 13 July 2009 ) was an Indian actor known for his roles in the Marathi language movies and Marathi theatre .
Anthony Clifford Allison ( 21 August 1925 -- 20 February 2014 ) was a South African geneticist and medical scientist who made pioneering study on the genetic resistance to malaria .
Barnard Flower ( died July or August 1517 ) was a Flemish glazier .
Claudinei Resende ( 27 May 1978 -- 6 November 2004 ) was a Brazilian football player who played for the Swedish club Helsingborgs IF .
Barry Metcalfe ( 28 September 1935 -- 3 April 1980 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played a game with Hawthorn in the VFL and spent the early 1960s at Claremont .
Richard Golden ( 1854 - -1909 ) was a noted comedy actor of the stage whose most famous role was `` Old Jed Prouty '' in his play of the same name .
Almamy Suluku ( born 1820 - 1906 ) was a powerful Limba ruler from Sierra Leone who maintained his independence as long as possible through brilliant political strategy .
Henry Thomas Hamblin ( 19 March 1873 -- 28 October 1958 ) was an English mystic and New Thought author .
William of Koppenbach ( died 1374 ) was bishop of Pécs in the Kingdom of Hungary from 1361 to his death in 1374 .
Cevherriz Hanımefendi ( c. 1863 - 1940 ) was the wife sixth wife of Murad V , deposed Ottoman Sultan .

Albert Bythesea Weigall CMG , ( 16 February 1840 -- 20 February 1912 ) was an English - born Australian schoolmaster , headmaster of Sydney Grammar School for 45 years .
Jissaku Nakamura ( 中村 十作 1867 - 1943 ) was born in Joetsu , Niigata Prefecture and devoted himself to the abolition of the notorious Nintozei taxation or poll tax enforced in Miyako and Yaeyama Islands .

Trygve Lange - Nielsen ( 9 July 1921 -- 18 April 2014 ) was a Norwegian barrister and judge .

Essington Lewis , CH ( 13 January 1881 -- 2 October 1961 ) was an Australian industrialist .

Frank Brieff ( 19 April 1912 -- 22 November 2005 ) was an American musician and conductor .
Mícheál Ó Lócháin ( 1836 -- 1899 ) was one of the foremost activists on behalf of the Irish language in the United States .
John O. Aalberg ( 3 April 1897 -- 30 August 1984 ) was a Hollywood sound technician who worked on films including Citizen Kane and It 's a Wonderful Life .
Raimbaud was an Italo - Norman chief who served under Philaretus Brachamius from 1073 to 1074 .
Andrew Saunders ( 22 September 1931 -- 13 March 2009 ) was an internationally recognised expert in artillery fortifications and Chief Inspector of Ancient Monuments and Historic Buildings in the UK between 1973 and 1989 .
Diego Martínez de Villamayor ( died 5 November 1176 ) was a noble of the Kingdom of Castile from the house of the counts of Bureba , who was very influential at court .
Harindra Dave ( 19 September 1930 - 29 March 1995 ) was a Gujarati writer of the post - independence period .
Gerard Horenbout ( c. 1465 - -c . 1541 ) was a Flemish miniaturist , a late example of the Flemish Primitives .
Harold McCarthy ( 28 October 1892 -- 1970 ) was an early and important British film critic .
Jacob Obermeyer ( 21 March 1845 in Steinhart -- 1 March 1938 in Würzburg ) was a Bavarian Jewish oriental researcher , scholar and a traveler , and the grandfather of the Israeli agent Meir Max Bineth .
Li Shuwen ( Chinese : 李书文 ) ( 1864 - -1934 ) was a master practitioner of the Chinese martial art of Bajiquan .
Ludvig Puusepp ( also Pussep or Pousep , rus . Людвиг Мартынович Пуссеп ) , ( 3 December ( O.S. 21 November ) 1875 , Kiev -- 19 October 1942 , Tartu ) was an Estonian surgeon and researcher and the world 's first professor of neurosurgery .
Aileen Britten ( 1916 - -1986 ) was an Australian actress of stage , film , TV and radio .
Maka Jiba ( died 1764 ) was the ruler of Bundu in West Africa between around 1720 and 1764 .
Miles Gerard ( born about 1550 at Wigan ; executed at Rochester 13 ( 30 ? ) April , 1590 ) was an English Roman Catholic priest .
Hanna Segal ( born Hanna Poznanska ; 20 August 1918 -- 5 July 2011 ) was a British psychoanalyst and a follower of Melanie Klein .
Johan van Dorth or Jan van Dorth ( 1574 in Salvador -- 17 July 1624 in Salvador ) , schout of Lochem , Lord of Horst and Pesch , was a nobleman and general of the Dutch Republic .
Wanniaarachchige Don David Victor Jayamanne ( 15 February 1915 - -25 July 1981 ) , popularly known as Eddie Jayamanne was a popular Sri Lankan comedian and actor of early Sri Lankan cinema .
Mary Bosanquet Fletcher ( 12 September 1739 - 8 December 1815 ) was an English deaconess in the early Methodist movement .
Alma Denenholz Kaplan ( 1906 -- 1 March 2003 ) was an American poet and syndicated columnist who wrote under the pseudonym Alma Denny .
Cai Jing ( 1047 - -1126 ) , courtesy name Yuanchang ( 元長 ) , was a government official and calligrapher who lived in the Northern Song Dynasty .
Ole Arntzen ( 4 February 1910 -- 7 August 1973 ) was a Norwegian businessman and resistance member during World War II . He was a brother of Sven Arntzen .
Hywel ap Syr Mathew ( died 1581 ) was a Welsh poet , genealogist and soldier .
Cheng Wing Kwong ( Zheng Rongguang ) ( Chin : 鄭榮光 , 1903 - -1967 ) was a disciple ( Tudi ) of Wu Jianquan , the founder of Wu Style Taijiquan .
Mohanmullji Chordia died in 1983 at the age of 81 , leaving behind five sons and three daughters .
John William Parker ( 1792 -- 1870 ) was an English publisher and printer .
Blessed Bartolomé Blanco Márquez ( 25 November 1914 -- 2 October 1936 ) was a secretary of Catholic Action and a delegate to the Catholic Syndicates .

Armando Villegas ( 1926 -- 29 December 2013 ) was a Peruvian - born Colombian painter , whose career spanned nearly six decades .
Edmund Doubleday ( died December 1620 ) was an English vintner , lawyer , office - holder and politician who sat in the House of Commons in 1614 .
Siaosi Vuna Takitakimālohi ( c. 1844 -- January 1862 ) was a Prince of Tonga , the only legitimate son and heir to King George Tupou I.
Albert Nightingale ( 10 November 1923 -- 27 February 2006 ) was a professional footballer who played as a striker for Sheffield United , Huddersfield Town , Blackburn Rovers and Leeds United .
John White Chadwick ( 19 October 1840 -- 11 December 1904 ) was an American writer and clergyman of the Unitarian Church .
Rhoda Sutherland ( 1907 -- 6 January 1989 ) was an academic who studied the French language and specialised in Old French and Old Provencal .
Thomas William Lyster ( 1855 - -1922 ) was director of the National Library of Ireland in Dublin between 1895 and his retirement in 1920 .
Heinrich Benno Möschler ( 28 October 1831 in Herrnhut -- 21 November 1888 in Kronförstchen , near Bautzen ) was a German entomologist specialised in Lepidoptera .
Ann Cooper Whitall ( 1716 - -1797 ) was a prominent Quaker woman in early America .
Monsignor Basil Shereghy ( 1918 -- 1988 ) was a leading Ruthenian Catholic Church priest and professor , as well as a cultural activist for Rusyns in the United States .
Lieutenant Colonel Gordon Grimsley King DSO ( 22 September 1918 -- 2009 ) was an officer of the Australian Army during the Second World War .
John Bedford ( c. 1720 - -1791 ) was an English iron worker and industrialist .
Thomas Hayton Mawson ( 5 May 1861 -- 14 November 1933 ) , known as T. H. Mawson , was a British garden designer , landscape architect , and town planner .
Baca Kurti ( c. 1807 - -1881 ) was an Albanian freedom fighter who participated in the Battle of Ržanica against the Principality of Montenegro .
Adolphe Biarent ( 16 October 1871 -- 4 February 1916 ) was a Belgian composer , conductor , cellist and music teacher .
Vangel Kodžoman ( Macedonian : Вангел Коџоман ) ( 1904 - 1994 ) was a Macedonian painter .
Abdoulaye Sékou Camara ( 17 November 1985 -- 27 July 2013 ) , better known as Sékou Camara , was a Malian footballer .

Arnljot Høyland ( 19 February 1924 -- 21 December 2002 ) was a Norwegian mathematical statistician .
Aina Karlsone ( born 13 November 1935 - -17 December 2012 ) was a Latvian artist and author .
Samuel Bishop ( 21 September 1731 -- 17 November 1795 ) was a poet born in London , and educated at Merchant Taylors ' School and Oxford University .
James Burbage ( 1530 - -35 -- 2 February 1597 ) was an English actor , theatre impresario , joiner , and theatre builder in the English Renaissance theatre .
Ali Reza Khan Azod al - Molk ( 11 October 1847 -- 22 September 1910 ) was an Iranian politician who acted as regent for the last ruling member of the Qajar dynasty .
Ernest Addison Moody ( 1903 - -1975 ) was a noted philosopher , medievalist , and logician as well as a musician and scientist .
Sir William Pepperrell , 1st Baronet ( 27 June 1696 -- 6 July 1759 ) was a merchant and soldier in Colonial Massachusetts .
Karl von Lützow ( 25 December 1832 -- 22 April 1897 ) was a German art historian and critic .
Nicholas Charles or Carles ( died 1613 ) was an English officer of arms , the Lancaster Herald between 1609 - 1613 .
Leonidas Palaskas ( Greek : Λεωνίδας Παλάσκας , 1819 -- 14 January 1880 ) was a distinguished Greek naval officer who served in the French and in the Greek navies , as well as publishing a number of scientific studies .
Robert McKinlay ( 10 October 1932 -- 27 August 2002 ) , known as Bob McKinlay or Bobby McKinlay , was a Scottish professional footballer who played as a centre half .
Francesco Bissolo ( 1470 - 72 - 20 April 1554 ) was a Venetian painter of the Renaissance .
Kurt Herbert Adler ( 2 April 1905 -- 9 February 1988 ) was an Austrian - born American conductor and opera house director .
Juan de Quevedo ( es : Vejorís , c. 1450 -- December 24 , 1519 in Barcelona ) was a Spanish Franciscan priest and the first Bishop Diocese of Santa María de La Antigua del Darién in Panama ( 1513 - 1519 ) .
Serafino Cavalli ( died 1578 ) was the Master of the Order of Preachers from 1571 to 1578 .
Fruzhin ( Bulgarian : Фружин ; also transliterated Fružin or Frujin ; died c. 1460 ) was a 15th - century Bulgarian noble who fought actively against the Ottoman conquest of the Second Bulgarian Empire .
Allectus ( died 296 ) was a Roman - Britannic usurper - emperor in Britain and northern Gaul from 293 to 296 .
Mutukan ( Mö'etüken ) was killed during the siege of Bamiyan in 1221 .
Johanne Rambusch ( 1865 - 1944 ) was a Danish feminist and politician , ( Danish Social Liberal Party ) .
Niels Fredriksen Dyhren ( 16 February 1778 -- 25 August 1866 ) was a Norwegian farmer and non - commissioner military officer .
Louis Couperin ( c. 1626 -- 29 August 1661 ) was a French Baroque composer and performer .
John Erasmus Blackett ( 1 January 1729 -- 11 June 1814 ) was a Newcastle upon Tyne businessman and Mayor of Newcastle after whom Blackett Street in central Newcastle is named .
Captain John Guy Dollman BA , FLS ( 1886 - -1942 ) , known as Guy Dollman , was a British zoologist and taxonomist .
Elena Puw Morgan ( 1900 -- 1973 ) was a Welsh writer who won the Literary Medal at the Cardiff National Eisteddfod in 1938
William McKinney ( 17 September 1895 -- 14 October 1969 ) was an American jazz drummer who led a series of musical groups , most notably McKinney 's Cotton Pickers .
Thomas Allason ( 1790 - -1852 ) was an English architect , surveyor and landscaper , noted in particular for his work at Connaught Square and the Ladbroke Estate in Kensington .
Richard Kirwan , LL.D , FRS , MRIA ( 1 August 1733 -- 22 June 1812 ) was an Irish scientist .
Uldarico A. Alviola ( 1883 - -1966 ) was a Filipino Visayan novelist , one of the most important Cebuano language writers .
Salomon Sweers ( Nijmegen , 15 June 1611 - Amsterdam , 2 March 1674 ) was a bookkeeper and a counsel for the Dutch East India Company .
Frederick Parris ( 20 September 1867 - 17 January 1941 ) was a first - class cricketer and Test match umpire .
Ángel de Estrada ( 1872 - -1923 ) was an Argentine poet , novelist and writer .
Maharana Amar Singh I , the Maharana of Mewar ( 16 March 1559 - 26 January 1620 ) , was the eldest son and successor of Maharana Pratap of Mewar .
André Vanderdonckt was a French cyclist , born 29 February 1908 in Flers - lez - Lille , died 5 August 1982 in Wattrelos .
Ignacio Manuel Altamirano Basilio ( 1834 -- 13 February 1893 ) was a Mexican writer , journalist , teacher and politician .
The Most Venerable Etai Yamada ( 1900 - -1999 ) was the 253rd head priest of the Japanese Tendai school of Mahayana Buddhism .
Cornelius Brown ( 5 March 1852 in Lowdham , Nottinghamshire -- 4 November 1907 ) was a British journalist and historian .
Sun Guangxian ( Chinese : 孫光憲 ; died 968 ) , courtesy name Mengwen ( 孟文 ) , self - styled Baoguangzi ( 葆光子 ) , was an official of the Chinese Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms Period state Jingnan ( Nanping ) .
Mary Ellen Hopkins ( 1932 - 2013 ) was an American quilter and author .
Santos Franco Sánchez ( 6 July 1942 - 2 February 1954 ) was a Spanish boy who is being considered for sainthood by the Roman Catholic Church .
Anastase Alfieri ( March 23 , 1892 Alexandria -- 1971 Cairo ) was an Italian entomologist who worked principally on Coleoptera but , also , with Hermann Preisner , on Heteroptera .
Otton Mieczysław Żukowski ( Bełz on the Sołokija , 1867 - 1931 ) was a Polish composer .
Joseph Charles Benziger ( 1762 - -1841 ) was the founder of the Catholic publishing house which bears his surname .
John Brande Trend , or J.B. Trend ( 1887 - -1958 ) , was a British Hispanist and the first Professor of Spanish at the University of Cambridge .
Cao Zhen ( died 231 ) , courtesy name Zidan , was a military general serving under the warlord Cao Cao in the late Eastern Han Dynasty .
Fuller Potter ( April 24 , 1910 -- 1990 ) was an American Abstract expressionist artist .
Jonkheer Pieter Maria Frans van Meeuwen ( 1837 ' s - Hertogenbosch- 1913 ' s - Hertogenbosch ) , was a Dutch jurist and president of the court of justice .
Colonel Henry Thomas Fenwick , CMG , DSO , MVO ( 20 December 1863 -- 30 August 1939 ) was a British army officer and Liberal Party politician .
One year later , on January 9 , 1967 , Clyde X 's home was bombed , but he was unhurt .
Gregorio Petrocchini ( 1535 - 19 May 1612 ) was an Italian cardinal at the end of sixteenth and early seventeenth century .
Stratis Myrivilis ( Greek : Στράτης Μυριβήλης , pseudonym of Efstratios Stamatopoulos ( Ευστράτιος Σταματόπουλος ) ; 30 June 1890 -- 19 July 1969 ) was a Greek writer .
Ștefan Achim ( 1930 - -2007 ) was a Romanian weightlifting coach , weightlifter and military officer , the last rank held by him in the army was colonel .
Walter Herold ( 10 August 1897 -- 28 November 1944 ) was a highly decorated Generalmajor in the Wehrmacht during World War II who commanded several divisions .
Marko Pohlin ( 13 April 1735 -- 4 February 1801 ) , was a Slovene philologist and author .
Tom Curry ( 1 September 1894 -- 6 February 1958 ) was an English footballer who played as a half back for Newcastle United and Stockport County in the 1920s .
King Sosurim of Goguryeo ( died 384 ) ( r. 371 - -384 ) was the 17th ruler of Goguryeo , the northernmost of the Three Kingdoms of Korea .
Kanichi Yamamoto ( 1879 - -1961 ) was the first Japanese Bahá'í .
William Rowley Elliston OBE , TD , BA , LLB ( 1 February 1869 -- 12 February 1954 ) , was a British judge and Liberal Party politician .
John Sterne was appointed Bishop of Colchester to deputise within the Diocese of Ely under the provisions of the Suffragan Bishops Act 1534 in 1592 and held the post until his death in 1607 .
Alfredo Boloña Jiménez ( December 24 , 1890 -- 1964 ) was a Cuban guitarist who played a role in the early development of the son as director of the Sexteto Boloña .
Abraham Teniers ( 1 March 1629 -- 26 September 1670 ) was a member of the Flemish artist family Teniers who specialized in genre paintings of villages , inns and monkey scenes .
Sigrid Arnoldson ( 20 March 1861 -- 7 February 1943 ) was a Swedish opera singer with an active international career at the end of the 19th century and into the 20th .
Thomas Bilney ( c. 1495 -- 19 August 1531 ) was an English Christian martyr .
Neil L. Whitehead ( 19 March 1956 -- 22 March 2012 ) was an English anthropologist , who is best known for his work on the anthropology of violence , dark shamanism ( and Guyanese kanaimà in particular ) , post - human anthropology and the historical anthropology of South America and the Caribbean .
Sir Charles John Crompton ( 1797 - -1865 ) , justice of the queen 's bench , born at Derby on 12 June 1797 , was the third son of Dr. Peter Crompton , and his second cousin Mary , daughter of John Crompton of Chorley Hall , Lancashire .

Ensign Jeremy Lister ( 1752 - -1836 ) was a British officer in the 10th Regiment of Foot during the early days of the American Revolution .
Ron McCann ( 25 June 1913 -- 15 February 1996 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Collingwood in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Anne Dreydel OBE ( 27 May 1918 -- 3 July 2007 ) was the co - founder of the Oxford English Centre , which later became St Clare 's , Oxford .
Vang Pao ( Hmong : Vaj Pov ; 8 December 1929 -- 6 January 2011 ) was a Major General in the Royal Lao Army .
Anna Eva Fay Pingree ( 1851 - 1927 ) was a famous medium and stage mentalist of the twentieth century .
Brigadier Mohammad Abbas Baig ( Urdu : برگیڈیر جنرل محمد عباس بیگ ) ( September 1917 -- 19 April 2008 ) was a Pakistan Army one - star general officer .
Georg Baresch Jiří Bareš ( 1585 - -1662 ) was Czech antique collector from Prague known for his connection to the Voynich manuscript .
Antonis Tritsis ( Greek : Αντώνης Τρίτσης ; 1937 -- 7 April 1992 ) was a Greek politician and urban planner , born and raised in the town of Argostoli on the island of Cefalonia .
Philip R. Rosendahl ( 31 May 1893 -- 4 October 1974 ) was the acting governor of the Danish colony of North Greenland from 1925 to 1928 and the governor from 1929 to 1939 .
Cirilo Vila Castro ( 7 October 1937 -- 23 July 2015 , Santiago ) was a Chilean composer , pianist , and academic , and the winner of the National Prize of Art in 2004 .
Lawrence J. Lee ( November 4 , 1932 in St. Louis , Missouri - 1991 ) is an American politician who served in the Missouri Senate .
Henry III the White ( Polish : Henryk III Biały ) ( 1227/1230 -- 3 December 1266 ) was a Duke of Wrocław from 1248 until his death ( as co - ruler with his brother ) .
Thomas McKee ( c. 1770 -- 20 October 1814 ) was a Canadian soldier and political figure .
Archbishop Samineni Arulappa ( 28 August 1924 -- 13 February 2005 ) , often shortened to S Arulappa , was an Indian Roman Catholic clergyman who served as the Archbishop of Hyderabad from December 1971 through January 2000 .
Saint Bernulf or Bernold of Utrecht ( died 19 July 1054 ) was Bishop of Utrecht ( 1026/27 - -1054 ) .
Patrick Dalzel - Job ( 1 June 1913 -- 14 October 2003 ) , was a distinguished British Naval Intelligence Officer and Commando of World War II . He was also an accomplished linguist , author , mariner , navigator , parachutist , diver and skier .
Harry Eltringham FRS ( 18 May 1873 , South Shields - 26 November 1941 , Stroud ) was an English histologist and entomologist who specialised in Lepidoptera .

Admiral Sir Richard King , 1st Baronet ( 10 August 1730 -- 7 November 1806 ) was a British naval officer and colonial governor .

Nigel Tetley ( c. 1924 -- 2 February 1972 ) was the first person to circumnavigate the world solo in a trimaran .
Saint Antiochus of Sulcis ( died c. 127 AD ) was an early Christian martyr of Sardinia .
John Mackenzie Bacon , FRAS ( 19 June 1846 -- 26 December 1904 ) was an English astronomer , aeronaut , and lecturer .
Todor Slavov ( Bulgarian : Тодор Славов ; 22 January 1984 -- 28 June 2015 ) was a Bulgarian rally driver .
Frank R. Day ( 1853 - -1899 ) was an entrepreneur in Los Angeles and Monterey , California , in the late 19th Century and was a member of the governing bodies of both cities .
Inga Bjørnson ( 4 March 1871 -- 8 March 1952 ) was a Norwegian philanthropist and theatre leader .
Margarete Garvin Gillin ( 1833 - 1915 ) was a painter of portraits and still lifes born in Brantford , Ontario .
Peter Baillie ( 1771 - 1 September 1811 ) was a British West Indies merchant , and Whig politician who sat in the House of Commons from 1807 to 1811 .
General George Ramsay , 9th Earl of Dalhousie GCB ( 23 October 1770 -- 21 March 1838 ) , styled Lord Ramsay until 1787 , was a Scottish soldier and colonial administrator .
Alexander Gregg ( 1819 - -1893 ) , an Episcopal clergyman , was the first bishop of Texas .
Félix María Zuloaga Trillo ( 31 March 1813 -- 11 February 1898 ) was a Mexican general and a Conservative leader in the War of Reform .
Sir George Rivers ( 1553 - -1630 ) was an English politician .
Adolf Lesser ( May 22 , 1851 - 1926 ) was a German physician who specialized in forensic medicine .
Anton Funtek ( 30 October 1862 -- 21 October 1932 ) was a Slovene writer , poet , editor and translator .
Józef Gąsienica ( 23 March 1941 -- 14 May 2005 ) was a Polish nordic combined skier who competed in the late 1960s and early 1970s .
Josiah Zion Gumede , OLG ( 19 September 1919 -- 28 March 1989 ) was the only president of the self - proclaimed , and internationally unrecognised , state of Zimbabwe Rhodesia during 1979 , before Rhodesia briefly reverted to British rule until the country 's independence as Zimbabwe in 1980 .
Charles Nicholas Paul Phipps ( 4 November 1845 -- 9 December 1913 ) , of Chalcot House , Westbury , Wiltshire , was a Brazil merchant , Conservative MP for Westbury ( 1880 - -1885 ) and High Sheriff of Wiltshire ( 1888 ) .
Lalla Aisha Mubarka , often referred to as Zaydana or Zaidana ( died 1716 ) , was the chief spouse of sultan Ismail Ibn Sharif of Morocco ( r. 1672 - -1727 ) .
Johannes Matelart ( also Matelart , Matellarto , Matelarte and other variations ; first name sometimes Ioanne or Jean ) ( before 1538 -- 7 June 1607 ) was a Flemish composer of the late Renaissance , active in Flanders , Bonn , and Rome .
John Hardyng ( or Harding ) ( 1378 - -1465 ) , English chronicler , was born in the north .
Pastor Oropeza Riera ( 12 October 1901 -- 9 July 1991 ) , born in Carora , Lara State , Venezuela , was a renowned pediatrician and one of the most prominent medical personalities in Venezuela .
Binnya Ran I ( Burmese : ပထမ ဗညားရံ , pronounced : ( pətʰəma̰ bəɲá jàɴ ) ; Mon : ဗညားရာံ ; 1393 - -1446 ) was king of Hanthawaddy Pegu from 1424 to 1446 .
Harry Equid ( 8 October 1923 -- 2 February 1984 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played for Essendon in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) during the 1940s .
Daniel Perrin ( 1642 - -1719 ) was one of the first permanent European inhabitants of Staten Island , New York .
Maniben Patel ( 3 April 1903 , Karamsad-1990 ) was an Indian independence movement activist and a Member of the Indian parliament .
Hibbert Binney ( 12 August 1819 -- 30 April 1887 ) was a Canadian Church of England bishop .
Berta Rosenbaum Golahny ( February 7 , 1925 -- November 4 , 2005 ) was an American painter , printmaker , and sculptor .
Niall Ó Glacáin , or Nellanus Glacanus ( c. 1563 - -1653 ) was an Irish physician active in Italy .
Epameinondas Kavvadias ( Greek : Επαμεινώνδας Καββαδίας , 1886 - -1965 ) was a Greek admiral who served thrice as Chief of the Navy General Staff and led the Greek fleet in the first years of World War II .
Jesse Elliston ( died 1853 ) was a proprietor of Elliston & Cavell , which became the leading department store in Oxford , England .
Harriet Gouldsmith ( 1787 -- 6 January 1863 ) was an English landscape painter and etcher .
Heinz Linge ( 23 March 1913 -- 9 March 1980 ) was an SS officer who served as a valet for German dictator Adolf Hitler .
Hugh Amherst , 4th Earl Amherst ( 30 January 1856 -- 7 March 1927 ) , styled The Honourable Hugh Amherst until 1910 , was a British peer , who succeeded to the earldom and its associated titles upon the death of his brother William in 1910 .
Sir Godfrey de Foljambe ( 1317 - -1376 ) was a prominent landowner and politician in fourteenth - century England who went on to have a successful career as an Irish judge , including a period as Lord Chief Justice of Ireland .
Barbara Mitchell ( 1929 , England -- 9 December 1977 , Richmond , London ) was an English actress who became a familiar face on British television in the 1960s and 1970s , best known for her work in many classic sitcoms of the period .
Rudolf Martin Meelführer ( 1670 - -1729 ) was a German Hebraist .
Anne Elder ( 4 January 1918 -- 23 October 1976 ) was an Australian ballet dancer and poet .
Carol Davila ( Romanian pronunciation : ( ˈkarol daviˈla ) ; 1828 -- 24 August 1884 ) was a prestigious Romanian physician of Italian ancestry .
Peter Pavel Glavar ( 2 May 1721 -- 24 January 1784 ) was a Carniolan Roman Catholic priest , beekeeper , writer , and businessman .
Shammai ( 50 BCE -- 30 CE , Hebrew : שמאי ) was a Jewish scholar of the 1st century , and an important figure in Judaism 's core work of rabbinic literature , the Mishnah .
Erna Weill ( 1904 - 1996 ) was an American German - Jewish sculptor known for her busts of 20th - century persons , in particular civil rights figures .
Robert Burdon Stoker ( 19 June 1859 -- 4 September 1919 ) was a British shipping magnate and Conservative politician .
Dietrich Opitz ( 13 January 1901 -- 2 January 1992 ) was a German assyriologist and colleague of Bruno Meissner .
Luigi Sincero ( 26 March 1870 -- 7 February 1936 ) was a Roman Catholic Cardinal and President of the Pontifical Commission for the Authentic Interpretation of the Code of Canon Law and Secretary of Sacred Congregation for the Oriental Churches , the title of Prefect held by the Popes from 1917 until 1967 .
Allan Ruthven ( 17 April 1922 -- 14 March 2003 ) was an Australian rules footballer in the ( then ) Victorian Football League .
Count Miksa Esterházy de Galántha ( Hungarian pronunciation : ( ˈmikʃɒ ˈɛstɛrhaːzi ) ; 14 May 1837 -- 5 August 1883 ) was a Hungarian landowner , diplomat and the founder of Magyar AC , the first sports association in Hungary .
James Hayllar ( 1829 - -1920 ) was an English genre , portrait and landscape painter .
Girolamo Troppa ( 1637 - -1710 ) was an Italian painter of the Baroque period , depicting mainly sacred subjects .
Dame Moura Lympany DBE ( 18 August 1916 -- 28 March 2005 ) was an English concert pianist .
Gerald Abramovitz ( 5 November 1928 -- 16 June 2011 ) was an architect and furniture designer .
Lieutenant General Sir Benjamin D'Urban GCB KCH FRS ( 1777 -- 25 May 1849 ) was a British general and colonial administrator , who is best known for his frontier policy when he was the Governor in the Cape Colony ( now in South Africa ) .
David Alfred Doudney ( 1811 - -1894 ) was an English printer , journalist and author , who became an evangelical clergyman .
Rasmus Hjort ( c.1525 -- 17 April 1604 ) was a Norwegian priest and humanist .
Björn Kjellström ( 9 September 1910 -- 26 August 1995 ) , originally from Sweden , was a ski orienteering champion in Sweden and co - founder of the compass manufacturing company Silva Sweden AB .
Jan Beijert ( 1928 , Smilde - 23 November 2007 , Delfzijl ) was a Dutch politician , director and columnist .
Daniel Connor ( 1831 - -12 January 1898 ) was a convict transported to Western Australia , who became one of the wealthiest men in the colony .
Stefano d'Antonio di Vanni ( c. 1405 - 1483 ) was an Italian Renaissance painter .
Javier Naranjo Villegas ( 21 January 1919 -- 7 March 2014 ) was a Colombian Prelate of Roman Catholic Church .
Olotoraca ( also spelled Olotaraca , Olotacara , or Otocara ; 1548 -- 1573 near Fort San Mateo , Florida ) was subchief of a Florida tribe .
Habib ibn al - Muhallab al - Azdi ( Arabic : حبيب بن المهلب الأزدي‎ ) ( died 720 ) was a provincial governor and military commander for the Umayyad dynasty , and a member of the Muhallabid family .
Yu Di ( 于頔 ) ( died 818 ) , courtesy name Yunyuan ( 允元 ) , formally initially Duke Li of Yan ( 燕厲公 ) and later Duke Si of Yan ( 燕思公 ) , was a general and official of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty .
Joseph Leeson , 1st Earl of Milltown ( 11 March 1701 -- 2 October 1783 ) was an Irish peer and politician .
Henry Langtry ( 1841 - -1892 ) was an Irish - born war hero of English descent who served as a colonel with the 3rd Dragoon Guards in the Abyssinian campaign in 1868 and was present at the storming and capture of Magdala .
The Rev. Dr . Thomas Cecil Fitzpatrick ( 27 August 1861 -- 28 October 1931 ) , was the President of Queens ' College , Cambridge , from 1906 until his death and Vice - Chancellor of Cambridge University from 1915 - -17 and 1928 - 29 .
Wang Dingbao ( 王定保 ) ( 870 - 941 ) was an official of the Chinese Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms Period state Southern Han , serving as a chancellor for less than a year .
Horace Vere , 1st Baron Vere of Tilbury ( 1565 -- 2 May 1635 ) ( also Horatio Vere or Horatio de Vere ) was an English military leader during the Eighty Years ' War and the Thirty Years ' War , a son of Geoffrey Vere and brother of Francis Vere .
James Keir FRS ( 20 September 1735 -- 11 October 1820 ) was a Scottish chemist , geologist , industrialist , and inventor , and an important member of the Lunar Society of Birmingham .
Woldemar Brinkmann ( 12 March 1890 -- 31 December 1959 ) was a German architect and interior designer , he is associated with Nazi architecture .
James Baylis Allen ( Birmingham 18 April 1803 -- 10 January 1876 London ) was an English line - engraver .
Katherine Burton ( born Katherine Kurz , 18 Mar 1887 , in Lakewood , near Cleveland , Ohio ; died September 22 , 1969 ) was an American Roman Catholic convert who became renowned in her post - conversion years as a religious biographer .
Askericus ( or Anscharic ) ( French : Anschéric ) ( died c. 890 ) was the Bishop of Paris from 886 until his death .
Przemko III , Duke of Opava ( also known as Přemek III or Primislaus III ; Czech : Přemysl III . Opavský ; German : Přemysl III . von Troppau ; c. 1450 -- 17 February 1493 ) was a member of the Opavian branch of the Bohemian Přemyslid dynasty .
Henry Spira ( 19 June 1927 -- 12 September 1998 ) was a Belgian - American animal rights advocate , widely regarded as one of the most effective animal advocates of the 20th century .
Kali Charan Banerjee ( 1847 - -1902 ) , spelt also as Kalicharan Banerji or K.C. Banerjea or K.C. Banurji , a Bengali convert to Anglican Church , was the founder of Calcutta Christo Samaj , a Christian parallel to Brahmo Samaj .
Martin Fynch or Finch ( 1628?--1698 ) was an English ejected minister .

Montford Scott ( b. in Norfolk , England ; executed at Fleet Street , London , on 2 July 1591 ) was an English Roman Catholic priest .
Jeane Daniel Gunder ( born 1888 , New York - died 1948 , Pasadena ) was an American entomologist who specialised in butterflies .
Sir Andrew Lauder of Fountainhall , 5th Baronet ( 8 May 1702 -- 6 March 1769 ) was a Burgess of the Royal Burgh of Lauder ( 1 August 1737 ) , and also of Musselburgh ( 8 June 1739 ) .
François Faber ( pronounced : ( fʁɑ̃.swa fa.be ) ; 26 January 1887 -- 9 May 1915 ) was a Luxembourgian / French racing cyclist .
Murong Yong ( Chinese : 慕容永 ; died 394 ) , courtesy name Shuming ( 叔明 ) , was the last emperor of the Xianbei state Western Yan .
James Hewetson ( c. 1797 - -1870 ) was a Texas empresario .
Dr. Radius Prawiro , Drs.ec.,AK ( 29 June 1928 in Yogyakarta -- 26 May 2005 in Germany ) was an Indonesian economist and politician .
John Solomon Rarey ( 1827 - -1866 ) was one of the nineteenth century horse whisperers , an important figure in the rehabilitation of abused and vicious horses during the 1850s .
Peter Gurney ( 9 March 1938 - 2 July 2006 ) was an author and campaigner for the rights and welfare of guinea pigs .
Cedar Paul , née Gertrude Mary Davenport ( 1880 -- 18 March 1972 ) was a singer , author , translator and journalist .
Abel J. Brown ( 1817 - -1894 ) , was a Lutheran pastor of Immanuel 's and Buehler 's ( or Beeler 's ) congregations in Sullivan County , Tennessee .
Paul Rosenfels ( 1909 , Chicago -- 1985 , New York ) was an American psychiatrist and psychoanalyst known as one of the first American social scientists to publish about homosexuality as part of the human condition , rather than defining it as an illness or deviation .
Mårten Eskil Winge ( 21 September 1825 -- 22 April 1896 ) was a Swedish artist especially known for his Norse mythology paintings .
Luis Arturo González López ( 21 December 1900 , Zacapa -- 11 November 1965 ) was a politician in Guatemala and the acting President of Guatemala on an interim basis , from 27 July 1957 to 24 October 1957 .
Niels Tønder Lund ( born 1749 - -died 1809 ) was a Danish zoologist .
William Muspratt ( 1759 - 1797 ) was an able seaman on His Majesty 's Armed Ship Bounty .
George Alexander Baird ( 30 September 1861 -- 18 March 1893 ) was a wealthy British race horse owner , breeder and the most successful amateur jockey ( gentleman rider ) of his day , who rode under the assumed name of Mr. Abington .
Iskandar - i Shaykhi ( Persian : اسکندر شیخی‎ ) , was ruler of the Afrasiyab dynasty from 1393 to 1403 .
Sarah Bezra Nicol ( died 1834 or after ) was a British actress who became known for playing older women character roles in Edinburgh .
Charles - Eusèbe Dionne ( 20 July 1846 -- 25 January 1925 ) , also known as Charles Eusebe or C. E. Dionne , was a French Canadian naturalist and taxidermist .
Sir Charles Cotterell ( 7 April 1615 -- 7 June 1701 ) , was an English courtier and translator .

Abraham of Kratia ( c. 474 -- c. 558 ) was a Christian monk from Syria .
Frederick Yeates Hurlstone ( 1800 - 10 June 1869 ) was an English portrait and historical painter .
Sunday Bada ( 22 June 1969 -- 12 December 2011 ) was a Nigerian sprinter who specialized in the 400 metres event .

Ingeborg of Norway ( Duchess Ingeborg , Old Norse Ingibjörg Hákonardóttir , Swedish Ingeborg Håkansdotter , Norwegian Ingebjørg Håkonsdatter ; 1301 -- 17 June 1361 ) , was a Norwegian and by marriage Swedish princess and royal duchess with a position in the regency governments in Norway ( 1319 - -27 ) and Sweden ( 1319 - -26 ) .
Paul Marin de la Malgue ( bap . 19 March 1692 -- 29 October 1753 ) was the eldest son of Charles - Paul Marin de la Malgue and Catherine Niquet .

Otto Staudinger ( 2 May 1830 -- 13 October 1900 ) was a German entomologist and a natural history dealer considered one of the largest in the world specialising in the collection and sale of insects to museums , scientific institutions , and individuals .
Dr. Sándor Kozma de Leveld ( 9 September 1825 -- 5 August 1897 ) was a Hungarian politician and jurist , who served as the first Crown Prosecutor of Hungary from 1872 to 1896 .

John Fenwicke ( c.1593 - -1670 ) , supported the parliamentary cause during the English Civil War .

Oldřich Kulhánek ( 26 February 1940 -- 28 January 2013 ) was a Czech painter , graphic designer , illustrator , stage designer and pedagogue .

Sir Charles Elliot , KCB ( 15 August 1801 -- 9 September 1875 ) , was a British naval officer , diplomat , and colonial administrator .
Antonios Katinaris ( Greek : Αντώνιος Κατινάρης ) ( 1931 -- 28 October 1999 ) was a Greek musician .

Torquato Conti ( 1591 - -1636 ) was an Italian military commander who served as a General - Field Marshal of the Holy Roman Empire during the Thirty Years ' War .

George Windsor Earl ( 1813 - -1865 ) was an English navigator and author of works on the Indian Archipelago .

Jim Mackie ( 31 December 1889 -- 20 March 1917 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Frederic Sutherland Ferguson ( 26 December 1878 , Stoke Newington , London -- 4 May 1967 , Isle of Wight ) was an English bibliographer .
James Cunningham , 7th Earl of Glencairn ( 1552 -- 1630 ) was a Scottish peer and member of the Privy Council of Scotland .
Henry Vanderburgh ( 1760 - -1812 ) was born in Troy , New York , in 1760 .

Bertrand I of Forcalquier was Count of Forcalquier from 1129 to 1144 .
Jörundur Garðar Hilmarsson ( 15 March 1946 -- 13 August 1992 ) , was an Icelandic linguist , scholar and grammarian specializing in comparative grammar of Indo - European languages .
James Beeching ( 1788 -- 7 June 1858 ) was an English boat builder .
John Pratt , pen name John Winton ( 3 May 1931 in London -- 27 April 2001 ) was an English author and obituarist , following a career in the Royal Navy in which he rose to Lieutenant - Commander .

Thomas Penny White ( 1777 , Marylebone , London - 24 July 1845 , Winchester ) was an English clergyman .
